AESO VPP Dispatch — Concepts & Theory Log
Week 1 — Data & EDA
The AESO Market

AESO (Alberta Electric System Operator) is the grid operator for Alberta's deregulated electricity market
Every hour, generators submit bids and AESO stacks them cheapest to most expensive to meet demand — this is called the merit order
The last (most expensive) generator needed to meet demand sets the price for everyone — this is the System Marginal Price (SMP), also called the pool price
Alberta's price cap is $1000/MWh

Alberta Internal Load (AIL)

AIL is the total electricity consumption in Alberta at any given hour, measured in MW
It follows strong diurnal (hour of day) and weekly patterns driven by human behavior
Alberta heating is mostly gas-based, so winter electricity spikes are less extreme than expected

Price Dynamics

Pool price is heavily right-skewed — median ~$45/MWh but mean ~$95/MWh due to spike events
10% of hours exceed $200/MWh, 4% exceed $500/MWh — spikes are not rare
Small changes in load (~15%) cause disproportionately large price swings (~240%) — this nonlinearity is called price elasticity
Prices peak at hour 17 (5pm) when residential and industrial demand overlap
Weekday prices are significantly higher than weekends from hour 6 onward — industries and businesses are closed on weekends
August has the highest monthly average due to AC load + extreme heat events in 2021–2022 pulling the average up

Why Probabilistic Forecasting

A deterministic model predicts a single value like "$55/MWh" — it completely misses tail risk
A probabilistic model says "90% chance price stays below $200, 5% chance it exceeds $500" — this is actionable for a VPP operator
The mean vs median gap ($95 vs $45) is proof that the distribution has a fat right tail that a point forecast ignores

Why This Matters for VPP Dispatch

A VPP aggregates distributed energy resources (batteries, solar, flexible loads) and bids their flexibility into the market
To bid intelligently, the VPP needs to know not just the expected price but the distribution of possible prices
If it knows there's a 10% chance of a $500 spike, it will hold battery capacity in reserve rather than discharge early
This is the core argument for the thesis — replace scenario sampling with calibrated probabilistic forecasts from a fine-tuned foundation model (Chronos)

Technical Vocabulary Learned

Merit order — stack of generator bids from cheapest to most expensive
Pool price / SMP — price set by the marginal (last) generator
AIL — Alberta Internal Load, total provincial electricity demand in MW
Price elasticity — disproportionate price response to small demand changes
Right-skewed distribution — most values cluster low, with a long tail of extreme high values
Diurnal pattern — repeating daily cycle (e.g. price peaks at 5pm every day)
Temporal features — hour, month, day of week used as model inputs
EDA (Exploratory Data Analysis) — visually and statistically understanding your data before modeling